@subsubsection An example of macro use


Let's say that @func{infix} is a syntactic keyword; we may have a
library like this:

@example
(library (infix)
  (export infix)
  (import (rnrs))
  (define-syntax infix
    (lambda (use) ---) ;this is the transformer function
    ))
@end example

@noindent
then in the following program S--expression:

@example
(import (rnrs) (infix))

(let-values (((port getter) (open-string-output-port)))
  (display (infix 1 + 2) port)
  (getter))
@end example

@noindent
the subexpression:

@example
(infix 1 + 2)
@end example

@noindent
is a @dfn{macro use} of the @func{infix} syntax and it becomes the
@dfn{input form} of the transformer function of @func{infix}; the input
form is extracted from the whole S--expression, transformed, let's say,
into the @dfn{output form}:

@example
(begin 3)
@end example

@noindent
and put back:

@example
(import (rnrs) (infix))

(let-values (((port getter) (open-string-output-port)))
  (display (begin 3) port)
  (getter))
@end example

A number of rules are used not to mess up bidings in the input and
output forms; these are introduced in @ref{stdlib syntax-case hygiene,
Hygiene}.

The single argument transformer functions are applied to is a
@dfn{syntax object} representing the input form; the standard defines
@dfn{wrapped syntax objects} and @dfn{unwrapped syntax objects}.  Both
wrapped and unwrapped objects can be used to represent the same
informations, but wrapped objects can be more efficient in terms of
consumed resources.

@c page
@node stdlib syntax-case intro unwrap
@subsubsection Unwrapping syntax objects


Let's focus on unwrapped syntax objects, which are easier to deal with;
it is always possible to convert a wrapped syntax object into an
unwrapped one by applying the @func{unwrap} function
defined in the following library (it is @strong{not} important to
understand it at first reading):

@example
(library (syntax-utilities)
  (export unwrap)
  (import (rnrs))
  (define (unwrap stx)
    (syntax-case stx ()
      (()
       '())
      ((?car . ?cdr)
       (cons (unwrap (syntax ?car))
             (unwrap (syntax ?cdr))))
      (#(?item ...)
       (list->vector (unwrap (syntax (?item ...)))))
      (?atom
       (identifier? (syntax ?atom))
       (syntax ?atom))
      (?atom
       (syntax->datum (syntax ?atom))))))
@end example

@noindent
it is possible to define alternative versions of this function with
different properties, depending on the intended usage.

Now let's define the following library:

@example
(library (try-it-macros)
  (export the-macro)
  (import (rnrs)
    (for (syntax-utilities) expand))
  (define-syntax the-macro
    (lambda (stx)
      (let ((sexp (unwrap stx)))
        (write sexp)(newline)
        #f))))
@end example

@noindent
the macro use in the following program:

@example
(import (rnrs) (try-it-macros))

(the-macro 1 hello #(ciao 2) 3 salut)
@end example

@noindent
will cause the input form to be unwrapped and bound to @code{sexp}, then
the S-expression is displayed as something like:

@example
(#<syntax the-macro>
 1
 #<syntax hello>
 #(#<syntax ciao> 2)
 3
 #<syntax salut>)
@end example

@noindent
we see that where symbols appear in the input form, in the unwrapped
syntax object we have @dfn{identifiers}: syntax objects holding only a
symbol marked with its originating lexical context.  We can process
@code{sexp} with the ordinary Scheme functions, then return an
S--expression holding datums and identifiers that do what we want.

