@subsubsection A transformer example


Here is an example implementation of the @func{receive} syntax, giving a
condensed interface to @func{call-with-values}:

@example
(import (rnrs) (for (syntax-utilities) expand))

(define-syntax receive
  (lambda (use)
    (let ((sexp (unwrap use)))
      (let ((formals          (cadr  sexp))
            (expression       (caddr sexp))
            (body             (cdddr sexp)))
        `(,(syntax call-with-values)
              (,(syntax lambda) () ,expression)
              (,(syntax lambda) ,formals . ,body))))))

(receive (a b)
    (values 1 2)
  (write 'ciao)
  (list a b))
@expansion{} (call-with-values
        (lambda ()
          (values 1 2))
      (lambda (a b)
        (write 'ciao)
        (list a b)))
@end example

The transformer of the @func{receive} macro extracts datums and
identifiers from the input form using the common list functions
@func{car}, @func{cdr}, @dots{} and, for simplicity, it performs no
checks to verify that the input form has the required structure (for
example: it does not check that the first element after the syntactic
keyword @func{receive} is a list of identifiers).

The @func{syntax-case} macro, exported by the library
@rsixlibrary{syntax-case}, provides a way to both extract elements from
a syntax object and to perform basic checks on its structure; it is
usually more convenient and efficient to use @func{syntax-case} for
macro--specific processing, rather than to unwrap the input form and
process the result.

