@subsubsection A quick look at the expander


Macro transformers are ordinary Scheme functions, which are written in
an @rnrs{6}--compatible Scheme language; the only difference from
ordinary functions, is that: transformer definitions are evaluated at
@dfn{expand time}, while ordinary function definitions are evaluated at
@dfn{run time}.  We take a look at how the expander works, avoiding
almost all the details and focusing on the languages.

Let's define a simple library to be used as language for run time:

@example
#!r6rs
(library (language-for-run)
  (export write newline quote define)
  (import (rnrs)))
@end example

@noindent
and a simple library to be used as language for expand time:

@example
#!r6rs
(library (language-for-expand)
  (export lambda syntax)
  (import (rnrs)))
@end example

@noindent
we use them in the following library, where we also import
@func{define-syntax} for run time:

@example
#!r6rs
(library (the-library)
  (export doit)
  (import (for (language-for-run) run)
    (for (language-for-expand) expand)
    (for (only (rnrs) define-syntax) run))

  (define (doit)
    (write (the-macro))
    (newline))

  (define-syntax the-macro
    (lambda (stx)
      (syntax (quote (1 2 3)))))
  )
@end example

@noindent
we can run the code with the following program:

@example
#!r6rs
(import (the-library))
(doit)
@end example

Let's point our attention to @library{the-library}.  After parsing the
@code{import} and @code{export} clauses, the expander scans the library
body; the @func{define-syntax} identifier is recognised as the one from
@library{rnrs}, so the transformer expression on its right--hand side:

@example
(lambda (stx)
  (syntax (quote (1 2 3))))
@end example

@noindent
is extracted and (not true, but we have to start from somewhere) we can
imagine it being evaluated with (notice the import levels):

@example
(define the-transformer
  (eval '(lambda (stx)
           (syntax (quote (1 2 3))))
        (environment
          '(for (language-for-run)    (meta -1))
          '(for (language-for-expand) run))))
@end example

@noindent
what's left of the library's body is:

@example
(define (doit)
  (write (the-macro))
  (newline))
@end example

@noindent
which is scanned for uses of @func{the-macro}; the use is found and the
transformer function applied to a syntax object holding
@code{(the-macro)}; the return value is a syntax object holding the
quoted list @code{(1 2 3)}, which is inserted in the body:

@example
(define (doit)
  (write (quote (1 2 3)))
  (newline))
@end example

The body can now be evaluated using bindings from
@library{language-for-run}.

