@subsection Identifier predicates


Identifiers are a basic concept of hygienic macro expansion: it is
possible to write macros with confidence only with a through
understanding of identifiers.  Let's analyse a simple form, which we can
imagine (for now) to appear at the top level of a program body:

@example
(let ((alpha 123))
  alpha)
@end example

@noindent
in it appear two distinct Scheme symbols: @samp{let} once, @samp{alpha}
twice; none of them appears in a quoted form, so all of them are
identifiers.  We have to acknowledge that the number of distinct
identifiers is three; the two instances of @samp{alpha} are
@strong{different} identifiers.

Moreover, the first instance of @samp{alpha} appears at the left side of
a @meta{bindings} element of the @func{let} syntax, so it is said to be
in ``binding position''; the second instance does not appear in a
binding position, so it is said to be in ``reference position''.
@ref{baselib expressions binding, Binding constructs}

@quotation
@strong{NOTE} In the following descriptions, the procedure arguments
with name @var{id} are meant to be syntax objects, each holding only an
identifier.
@end quotation


@deffn Procedure {identifier?} @var{obj}
Return @true{} if @var{obj} is an identifier, i.e., a syntax object
representing an identifier, and @false{} otherwise.

The @func{identifier?} procedure is often used within a fender to verify
that certain subforms of an input form are identifiers, as in the
definition of @code{rec}, which creates self--contained recursive
objects, below.

@example
(define-syntax rec
  (lambda (x)
    (syntax-case x ()
      ((_ x e)
       (identifier? #'x)
       #'(letrec ((x e)) x)))))

(map (rec fact
       (lambda (n)
         (if (= n 0)
             1
             (* n (fact (- n 1))))))
     '(1 2 3 4 5))
@result{} (1 2 6 24 120)

(rec 5 (lambda (x) x))
@error{} exception &syntax
@end example
@end deffn


The procedures @func{bound-identifier=?} and @func{free-identifier=?}
each take two identifier arguments and return @true{} if their arguments
are equivalent and @false{} otherwise.  These predicates are used to
compare identifiers according to their @emph{intended use} as free
references or bound identifiers in a given context.


@deffn Procedure {bound-identifier=?} @vari{id} @varii{id}
Return @true{} if a binding for one would capture a reference to the
other in the output of the transformer, assuming that the reference
appears within the scope of the binding; return @false{} otherwise.

In general, two identifiers are @func{bound-identifier=?} only if both
are present in the original program or both are introduced by the same
transformer application (perhaps implicitly, see @func{datum->syntax}).

Operationally, two identifiers are considered equivalent by
@func{bound-identifier=?} if and only if they have the same name and the
same marks.

The @func{bound-identifier=?} procedure can be used for detecting
duplicate identifiers in a binding construct or for other preprocessing
of a binding construct that requires detecting instances of the bound
identifiers.

For example, let's consider this macro:

@example
(define-syntax doit
  (lambda (stx)
    (syntax-case stx ()
      ((_ id1 id2)
       (begin
         (display (bound-identifier=? #'id1 #'id2))
         #'(let ((id1 123)) id2))))))
@end example

@noindent
in the following macro use the identifiers are
@func{bound-identifier=?}:

@example
(doit alpha alpha)
@result{} 123
@print{} #t
@end example

@noindent
because binding one in the output form of the macro use, ``captures''
the reference of the other one; in the following macro use the
identifiers are not @func{bound-identifier=?}:

@example
(let ((beta 456))
  (doit alpha beta))
@result{} 456
@print{} #f
@end example

@noindent
because binding one does not capture the reference of the other.
@end deffn


@deffn Procedure {free-identifier=?} @vari{id} @varii{id}
Return @true{} if and only if the two identifiers would resolve to the
same binding if both were to appear in the output of a transformer,
outside of any bindings inserted by the transformer.  Here is an example
showing that it is the origin of the bindings that matters, not the
actual symbol in the identifier:

@example
(import (rnrs)
  (prefix (only (rnrs) vector) that:))

(define-syntax doit
  (lambda (stx)
    (syntax-case stx ()
      ((_ id1 id2)
       (begin
         (display (free-identifier=? #'id1 #'id2))
         #f)))))

(doit vector that:vector)
@print{} #t
@end example

If neither of two like--named identifiers resolves to a binding, i.e.,
both are unbound, they are considered to resolve to the same binding;
example:

@example
(import (rnrs))

(define-syntax doit
  (lambda (stx)
    (syntax-case stx ()
      ((_ id1 id2)
       (begin
         (display (free-identifier=? #'id1 #'id2))
         #f)))))

;; ALPHA and BETA are unbound here

(doit alpha alpha)
@print{} #t

(doit alpha beta)
@print{} #f
@end example

Operationally, two identifiers are considered equivalent by
@func{free-identifier=?} if and only if: the topmost matching
substitution for each maps to the same binding or the identifiers have
the same name and no matching substitution.  Let's consider this
program:

@example
(import (rnrs))
(let ((alpha 123))
  (list alpha alpha))
@end example

@noindent
if we substitute @samp{alpha} with @samp{beta} in the @func{let} form:

@example
(import (rnrs))
(let ((beta 123))
  (list beta beta))
@end example

@noindent
we obtain an equivalent program; this is because the two @samp{alpha}
identifiers in the @func{list} form of the original program are
@func{free-identifier=?}.

As last examples, notice that in the following program:

@example
(import (rnrs))

(let ((alpha 123))
  (define beta alpha)
  (list alpha beta))
@end example

@noindent
@samp{alpha} and @samp{beta} in the @func{list} form are @strong{not}
@func{free-identifiers=?}; in the following program:

@example
(import (rnrs))

(let ((alpha 123))
  (let-syntax ((beta (identifier-syntax alpha)))
    (list alpha beta)))
@end example

@noindent
@samp{alpha} and @samp{beta} in the @func{list} form are still
@strong{not} @func{free-identifiers=?}.
@end deffn


The @func{syntax-case} and @func{syntax-rules} forms internally use
@func{free-identifier=?} to compare identifiers listed in the literals
list against input identifiers:

@example
(let ((fred 17))
  (define-syntax a
    (lambda (x)
      (syntax-case x ()
        ((_ id) #'(b id fred)))))
  (define-syntax b
    (lambda (x)
      (syntax-case x ()
        ((_ id1 id2)
         #`(list
             #,(free-identifier=? #'id1 #'id2)
             #,(bound-identifier=? #'id1 #'id2))))))
  (a fred))
@result{} (#t #f)
@end example

The following definition of unnamed @func{let} uses
@func{bound-identifier=?} to detect duplicate identifiers:

@example
(define-syntax let
  (lambda (x)
    (define (unique-ids? ls)
      (or (null? ls)
          (and (let notmem? ((x  (car ls))
                             (ls (cdr ls)))
                 (or (null? ls)
                     (and (not (bound-identifier=? x (car ls)))
                          (notmem? x (cdr ls)))))
               (unique-ids? (cdr ls)))))
    (syntax-case x ()
      ((_ ((i v) ...) e1 e2 ...)
       (unique-ids? #'(i ...))
       #'((lambda (i ...) e1 e2 ...) v ...)))))
@end example

@noindent
the argument @samp{#'(i ...)} to @func{unique-ids?} is guaranteed to be
a list by the rules given in the description of @func{syntax}.

With this definition of @func{let}:

@example
(let ((a 3) (a 4))
  (+ a a))
@error{} exception &syntax
@end example

@noindent
however:

@example
(let-syntax
    ((dolet (lambda (x)
              (syntax-case x ()
                ((_ b)
                 #'(let ((a 3) (b 4)) (+ a b)))))))
  (dolet a))
@result{} 7
@end example

@noindent
since the identifier @samp{a} introduced by @func{dolet} and the
identifier @code{a} extracted from the input form are not
@func{bound-identifier=?}.

Rather than including @samp{else} in the literals list as before, this
version of @func{case} explicitly tests for @samp{else} using
@func{free-identifier=?}.

@example
(define-syntax case
  (lambda (x)
    (syntax-case x ()
      ((_ e0 ((k ...) e1 e2 ...) ...
              (else-key else-e1 else-e2 ...))
       (and (identifier? #'else-key)
            (free-identifier=? #'else-key #'else))
       #'(let ((t e0))
           (cond
             ((memv t '(k ...)) e1 e2 ...)
             ...
             (else else-e1 else-e2 ...))))
      ((_ e0 ((ka ...) e1a e2a ...)
              ((kb ...) e1b e2b ...) ...)
       #'(let ((t e0))
           (cond
             ((memv t '(ka ...)) e1a e2a ...)
             ((memv t '(kb ...)) e1b e2b ...)
             ...))))))
@end example

With either definition of @func{case}, @samp{else} is not recognized as
an auxiliary keyword if an enclosing lexical binding for @samp{else}
exists.  For example,

@example
(let ((else @false{}))
  (case 0 (else (write "oops"))))
@error{} exception &syntax
@end example

@noindent
since @samp{else} is bound lexically and is therefore not the same
@samp{else} that appears in the definition of @func{case}.

